06219nam a22012375i 9781400885299DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984650546  a97814008852997 a10.1515/97814008852992doi  a(DE-B1597)479653  a(OCoLC)978892740  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aLA339.N5bS55 2018 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a370.97472231 aSims, Christo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisruptive Fixation :bSchool Reform and the Pitfalls of Techno-Idealism /cChristo Sims. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b1 line illus. 1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Culture and Technology ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Cycles of Disruptive Fixation -- t3. Spatial Fixations -- t4. Pedagogic Fixations -- t5. Amenable and Fixable Subjects -- t6. Community Fixations -- t7. Conclusion: The Resilience of Techno-Idealism -- tAppendix. Ethnographic Fixations -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn New York City in 2009, a new kind of public school opened its doors to its inaugural class of middle schoolers. Conceived by a team of game designers and progressive educational reformers and backed by prominent philanthropic foundations, it promised to reinvent the classroom for the digital age. Ethnographer Christo Sims documented the life of the school from its planning stages to the graduation of its first eighth-grade class. Disruptive Fixation is his account of how this "school for digital kids," heralded as a model of tech-driven educational reform, reverted to a more conventional type of schooling with rote learning, an emphasis on discipline, and traditional hierarchies of authority. Troubling gender and racialized class divisions also emerged.Sims shows how the philanthropic possibilities of new media technologies are repeatedly idealized even though actual interventions routinely fall short of the desired outcomes-often dramatically so. He traces the complex processes by which idealistic tech-reform perennially takes root, unsettles the worlds into which it intervenes, and eventually stabilizes in ways that remake and extend many of the social predicaments reformers hope to fix. Sims offers a nuanced look at the roles that powerful elites, experts, the media, and the intended beneficiaries of reform-in this case, the students and their parents-play in perpetuating the cycle.Disruptive Fixation offers a timely examination of techno-philanthropism and the yearnings and dilemmas it seeks to address, revealing what failed interventions do manage to accomplish-and for whom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunity and schoolzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEducational anthropologyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEducational changezNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEducational technologyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSocial changezNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAmerican school.  aDowntown School.  aNew York City.  aParent-Teacher Association.  aUnited States.  aamenable and fixable subjects.  aboundaries.  abullying.  acommunity fixations.  acommunity involvement.  adigital age.  adigital kids.  adisruptive fixation.  adisruptive fixations.  aeducation.  aeducational reform.  agender division.  aidealism.  aidentities.  aimminent collapse.  alearning environments.  alocal community.  amedia technology.  aparents.  apedagogic fixations.  aphilanthropic foundations.  a